    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-02-27T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-02-27T12:00:00-05:00" n="810"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d810">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">839.00 Revolutions/27: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Minister in the Dominican Republic</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Curtis</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-02-27T12:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 27, 1930—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>13. Department is advised by British Embassy that sloop <hi rend="italic"
                        >Wistaria</hi> will arrive at Santo Domingo from Dominica probably during
                    the course of today. Department still feels that the situation is not such as to
                    require the presence of a warship and especially that it would be very unwise to
                    land any forces. The landing of forces might well change the situation in a very
                    unfavorable manner by creating hostile <pb facs="0805" n="707" xml:id="pg_707"/>
                    feeling against foreigners in general and the nationals of the country landing
                    forces in particular. The Department’s information indicates that all sides at
                    the present time are scrupulously respecting all foreign interests. The landing
                    of foreign forces might well provoke a change in this attitude and very much
                    complicate the situation. The British Embassy here has been informed in the
                    above sense and you may also so inform your British colleague.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cotton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
